I"*<p>If <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/agitation-can-be-weaponized">agitation evolved to get us moving</a>, and if moving stops agitation from building up, such as with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optic-flow-modulates-autonomic-arousal">optic flow</a>, then <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/contrasting-difficulties-are-like-price-decoys">engaging in a challenging task</a> might decrease <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/body-seeks-homeostasis">stress</a>. The effort underlying the process might signal the body that the goal of the agitation build-up has been reached, and that thereâ€™s no need for more. Essentially, catharsis blunts the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/stress-weakens-prefrontal-hold-on-limbic-system">stress response</a>.</p>
